        <div n="928A79L1" type="poem"><head type="note" n="1" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-headnote-1"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-headnote-1-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-headnote-1-line-group-1-line-1">Written in or about the Year 1724.</l></lg></head><head type="note" n="2" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-headnote-2"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-headnote-2-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-headnote-2-line-group-1-line-1">XIX. On the G<hi rend="SMALL-CAPS">ALLOWS</hi>.</l></lg></head><head type="note" n="3" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-headnote-3"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-headnote-3-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-headnote-3-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head>
      <lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-1"><hi rend="display-initial">T</hi>HERE is a gate, we know full well,</l><l n="2" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-2"> That stands 'twixt heaven, and earth, and hell,</l><l n="3" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-3"> Where many for a passage venture,</l><l n="4" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-4"> Yet very few are fond to enter;</l><l n="5" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-5"> Although 'tis open night and day,</l><l n="6" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-6"> They for that reason shun this way:</l><l n="7" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-7"> Both dukes and lords abhor its wood,</l><l n="8" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-8"> They can't come near it for their blood.</l><l n="9" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-9"> What other way they take to go,</l><l n="10" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-10"> Another time I·'ll let you know.</l><l n="11" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-11"> Yet commoners with greatest ease</l><l n="12" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-12"> Can find an entrance when they please.</l><l n="13" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-13"> The poorest hither march in state</l><l n="14" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-14"> (Or they can never pass the gate),</l><l n="15" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-15"> Like Roman generals triumphant,</l><l n="16" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-16"> And then they take a turn and jump on·'t.</l><l n="17" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-17"> If gravest parsons here advance,</l><l n="18" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-18"> They cannot pass before they dance;</l><l n="19" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-19"> There·'s not a soul that does resort here,</l><l n="20" xml:id="spp-928A79L1-line-20"> But strips himself to pay the porter.928A79L1   </l></lg></div>
